        <title>Activity: To use a series of techniques to do calculations [LO 1.10]</title>
        <para id="id1169611320556"/>
        <para id="id1169617002460">1. The calculator is a wonderful aid for checking our calculations. If you know how to use the "constant function" of your calculator, an activity like the previous and following ones is child's play! See if you can complete the following arrow diagram with the aid of your calculator.</para>
        <list id="id1169611382736" list-type="bulleted">
          <item>What are you going to key in? ______________________________________ </item>
        </list>
        <figure id="id1169611608390">
          <media id="id1169611608390_media" alt="">
            <image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/graphics1-2c54.png" id="id1169611608390__onlineimage" height="152" width="586"/>
          </media>
        </figure>
        <para id="id1169617395650">2. Use the constant function of your calculator again and write down the numbers that appear on the screen when you key in the following:</para>
        <para id="id1169611759938">2.1 2 586 + 3 = = =    2 607</para>
        <para id="id1169611395369">__________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________</para>
        <para id="id1169615118538">2.2 7 839 + 100 = = =   8 539</para>
        <para id="id1169611481161">__________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________</para>
        <para id="id1169611421919"/>
        <para id="id1169617075537">2.3 8 213 + 10 000 = = =  88 213</para>
        <para id="id1169611558245">__________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________</para>
        <para id="id1169615191102"/>
        <para id="id1169615051525">You know by now that different peoples used different numerals to write down numbers. Let us take an in-depth look at the Romans' way of writing:</para>
        <para id="id1169611620260"/>
        <para id="id1169611497781">DO YOU STILL REMEMBER?  </para>
        <list id="id1169611769128" list-type="bulleted">
          <item>In the previous module we saw that the Roman numerals differed from ours.</item>
        </list>
